<gtr:projectOverview xmlns:gtr="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk/api"><gtr:projectComposition><gtr:collaborations/><gtr:leadResearchOrganisation url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/A0A585E0-6B0D-4643-A3A6-47943B4CBFEF"><gtr:id>A0A585E0-6B0D-4643-A3A6-47943B4CBFEF</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Liverpool</gtr:name><gtr:department>Law</gtr:department><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Senate House</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Abercromby Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Liverpool</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>L69 3BX</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>North West</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:typeInd>RO</gtr:typeInd></gtr:leadResearchOrganisation><gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:organisationRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/organisation/A0A585E0-6B0D-4643-A3A6-47943B4CBFEF"><gtr:id>A0A585E0-6B0D-4643-A3A6-47943B4CBFEF</gtr:id><gtr:name>University of Liverpool</gtr:name><gtr:address><gtr:line1>Senate House</gtr:line1><gtr:line2>Abercromby Square</gtr:line2><gtr:line4>Liverpool</gtr:line4><gtr:postCode>L69 3BX</gtr:postCode><gtr:region>North West</gtr:region><gtr:country>United Kingdom</gtr:country></gtr:address><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>LEAD_RO</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:organisationRole></gtr:organisationRoles><gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/635332F4-2326-4190-886E-4E324C1F3B49"><gtr:id>635332F4-2326-4190-886E-4E324C1F3B49</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Louise</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Helen</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Ackers</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/person/3818F3AE-3B13-4A9D-97D4-80A34A2441AC"><gtr:id>3818F3AE-3B13-4A9D-97D4-80A34A2441AC</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Fiona</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Beveridge</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>CO_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF017979%2F1"><gtr:id>DDEAEB82-7097-4333-8B39-148134AAA8BD</gtr:id><gtr:title>Building Research Capacity in Empirical Socio-Legal Research</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F017979/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>This project draws together researchers and academics from 6
universities - including Manchester, Sheffield, Loughborough,
Nottingham Trent, Bradford and Leeds - to deliver a series of workshops
aimed at encouraging and sustaining capacity in empirical socio-legal
research (ESLR). It aims to:&amp;nbsp;
&lt;br />

&lt;br />
&lt;ul>
 &lt;li>augment existing doctoral training, support doctoral researchers
and improve the quality of doctoral training and supervision in the
field of ESLR;&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>improve support for doctoral supervisors;&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>develop effective mentoring for mid career researchers in ESLR;&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>encourage the mainstreaming of the outputs of ESLR into curricula
at undergraduate and postgraduate level (as the basis of encouraging
'feeder-routes' and a new generation of researchers);&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>build a community of ESLR scholars based on a networking approach as the basis for sustainable capacity-building;&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>increase the take-up of existing specialised ESRC research training schemes amongst this community.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>




 In view of the identified needs for capacity-building in the field of
socio-legal research, the project activities are aimed at four broad
groups: (1) doctoral researchers engaged in socio-legal projects with
an empirical element; (2) early career researchers in HE; (3)
mid-career 'switchers' who have an established position and wish to
enhance their skills in ESLR (supervisors, mentors and independent
researchers); and (4) researchers employed outside of the academic
sector in private and NGO organisations.
